    "45950215": {
      "title": "Rigid spine muscular dystrophy due to SEPN1 mutation presenting as cor pulmonale",
      "abstract": "The nonspecific “rigid spine syndrome” (RSS) is characterized by restricted spine mobility, kyphoscoliosis, reduced vital capacity, and nonprogressive proximal weakness. A subgroup of patients is classified as having rigid spine muscular dystrophy (RSMD), a laminin-α2–positive congenital muscular dystrophy. RSMD linked to chromosome 1p35–361 is caused by mutation in the SEPN1 gene encoding selenoprotein N.2 ::: ::: We describe a patient with RSMD, homozygous for an SEPN1 mutation, who had life-threatening yet reversible right heart failure caused by severe involvement of the diaphragm with nocturnal hypoventilation and pulmonary hypertension. He improved with nocturnal ventilatory assistance. The clinical and genetic findings in his mother and seven siblings are also described. ::: ::: Born to nonconsanguineous healthy parents, the patient was the youngest of 10 children. Developmental motor milestones were normal. Slight difficulty running and climbing stairs, restricted neck movements, elbow contractures, and scoliosis were noted during childhood and adolescence. Family history was unremarkable. He presented at age 26 years with rapidly progressive respiratory and right heart failure with cough, orthopnea, interrupted …"
    }
  }
